<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920130-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>920130-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- ConAgra Inc.:   OSHA's Charges on Safety   Settled by $425,000 Penalty</HL><DATE>01/30/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9</SO><CO>   CAG LABOR</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><RE>MISSOURI (MO)NEBRASKA (NE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ConAgra Inc. agreed to pay $425,000 to settle charges bythe Occupational Safety and Health Administration that thecompany's turkey-processing unit violated record-keeping andother safety regulations.   In addition, the food concern's ConAgra Poultry unitagreed to establish an &quot;ergonomics management program&quot; underwhich ConAgra will retain one or more ergonomists to studythe work environment at its 21 poultry plants.</LP><TEXT>   Originally, OSHA had sought about $1 million forviolations it said it found in 1989 at a ConAgraturkey-processing plant in Carthage, Mo. The citationscovered 48 alleged instances of ergonomic hazards and 181alleged instances of improper recordkeeping. The companydidn't admit any wrongdoing in the settlement.   Meat-processing employees can suffer injury fromrepetitive motions required by their work on slaughter-houseprocessing lines. The ergonomics management program is&quot;designed to control cumulative trauma disorders such ascarpal tunnel syndrome among workers in ConAgra poultryprocessing plants,&quot; OSHA said.</TEXT></DOC>